Preheat your #oven{} to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9.

Quarter the @baby potatoes{1}. Halve any larger quarters.

Pop the potatoes onto a lined #baking tray{}.

Drizzle with @oil{to taste}, season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}. Spread out in a single layer.

Roast on the top shelf of your oven until golden and crispy, ~{25-35%mins}. Turn halfway through cooking.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

Pour @water{300%ml}(cold, salted) into a #medium pot{with a tight-fitting lid}.

Stir in the @rice{150%g} and bring to the boil.

Lower the heat to medium, cover, and cook for ~{10%mins}.

Once cooked, remove the pot from the heat.

Keep covered for ~{10%mins} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, trim the @green beans{150%g} and cut into thirds.

Drain the @sweetcorn{1%pack} in a #sieve{}.

Halve the @chilli{1} and discard the core and seeds. Finely chop.

Roughly chop the @coriander{5%g}(stalks and all).

Place a #large pot{} over high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

When hot, fry the sweetcorn and green beans together until charred, ~{3-4%mins}.

Reduce the heat to medium-high then add the @North Indian Style Spice Mix{1%sachet}, chilli (use less if you don't like spice) and @Rogan Josh Curry Paste{1%sachet}.

Mix well and fry until fragrant, ~{1%min}.

Add the @chopped tomato with onion & garlic{1%pack}, @water{75%ml}, @salt{1/2%tsp} and @sugar{1/2%tsp}.

Bring to a boil then reduce the heat and simmer until thickened slightly, ~{8-10%mins}.

Add a splash of water to loosen the curry if you feel it's become too thick.

Season to taste with salt and pepper.

Divide the curry between #bowls{}.

Scatter the roast potatoes over the top.

Spoon over a dollop of @yoghurt{75%g}.

Garnish to taste with any remaining chilli and a sprinkling of coriander.

Fluff up the rice with a fork and serve alongside.